Equilibrium occurs where quantity supplied
equals quantity demanded. What does it mean?

2
00:00:06,220 --> 00:00:12,110
Basically, your market price will be stable,
that is, it won't tend to change, when you

3
00:00:12,110 --> 00:00:16,859
reach the point at which willingness to buy
coincides with willingness to sell in the

4
00:00:16,859 --> 00:00:17,449
market.

5
00:00:17,449 --> 00:00:22,340
Here’s a numerical example. Note that I
could pick any numbers for my demand, as long

6
00:00:22,340 --> 00:00:27,320
as they follow one simple rule: as price goes
up, quantity demanded must go down. That's

7
00:00:27,320 --> 00:00:32,610
the Law of Demand. Similarly, for supply,
as price goes up quantity supplied must go

8
00:00:32,610 --> 00:00:35,289
up as well, to follow the Law of Supply.

9
00:00:35,289 --> 00:00:42,289
Without even looking at a diagram, where is
equilibrium? Equilibrium occurs at a price

10
00:00:42,610 --> 00:00:47,739
of three dollars, where the quantity demanded
equals the quantity supplied, at three units

11
00:00:47,739 --> 00:00:52,510
(please note that the fact that price and
quantity are both three is just coincidence;

12
00:00:52,510 --> 00:00:58,968
they will not always be the same). If I plot
out these numbers -- first the demand figures,

13
00:00:58,969 --> 00:01:04,140
then supply – I reach the same conclusion
with the diagram: equilibrium occurs at a

14
00:01:04,140 --> 00:01:09,000
price of three dollars where the quantity
supplied equals the quantity demanded at three

15
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:10,680
units.

16
00:01:10,680 --> 00:01:17,680
Why is this the equilibrium? Because no other
price would be stable. All other prices would

17
00:01:17,930 --> 00:01:23,299
have a tendency to change. At a dollar, for
instance, the buyers are happy (they’d love

18
00:01:23,299 --> 00:01:28,320
to buy five units); but the sellers are unhappy
-- they're only willing to provide one unit

19
00:01:28,320 --> 00:01:33,199
to the market. A situation like this, where
the quantity demanded is greater than the

20
00:01:33,200 --> 00:01:38,990
quantity supplied, is referred to as a shortage,
and will result in upward pressure on price.

21
00:01:38,990 --> 00:01:44,669
Why? Well, those buyers all want to purchase,
but there's only one unit available, so the

22
00:01:44,670 --> 00:01:50,469
buyers start to compete to get the one available
unit -- by offering more money. Price goes

23
00:01:50,469 --> 00:01:56,658
up, and consequently quantity demanded drops,
and quantity supplied rises until we get to

24
00:01:56,659 --> 00:01:57,200
equilibrium.

25
00:01:57,200 --> 00:02:04,200
What about a higher price, like five dollars?
At five dollars, sellers are happy providing

26
00:02:04,340 --> 00:02:10,020
five units, but buyers are unhappy: they only
want one unit. When the quantity demanded

27
00:02:10,020 --> 00:02:14,900
is less than the quantity supplied, we have
a surplus, and price will drop.

28
00:02:14,900 --> 00:02:21,360
OK, let's go back to the housing market example.
Price P1 is the stable market equilibrium

29
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:27,370
price for this market. What if it's not the
price? Start by taking a look at the Phoenix

30
00:02:27,370 --> 00:02:34,370
